Gillespie algorithm

SI_tau <- function (x, params) {
S <- x[2]
I <- x[3]
N <- S+I
beta <- params["beta"]
## Rates
rates <- c(
infection=beta*S*I/N
)
## Transition matrix with changes in each event
transition_matrix <- list(
infection=c(-1,1)
)
## Sum of all events
total_rates <- sum(rates)
## Time to the next event
if (total_rates==0)
tau <- Inf
else
tau <- rexp(n=1,rate=total_rates)
## Decide which event will occur
next_event <- sample.int(n=length(rates),size=1,prob=rates/total_rates)
return(x + c(tau, transition_matrix[[next_event]]))
}

SI model without demography

nsims <- 10
N <- 100
xstart <- tibble(time=0,S=N-1,I=1) #initial conditions
params <- c(beta=0.2) #parameters
output_all <- tibble(NULL)
for(i in 1:nsims){
x <- as_vector(xstart)
output <- xstart %>% mutate(ID = i)
while ((x["time"] < 200) && (x["S"] > 0)) {
x <- SI_tau(x,params)
output <- output %>% bind_rows(x) %>% mutate(ID = i)
}
output_all <- output_all %>% bind_rows(output)
}
output_all %>% ggplot(aes(time, I, group=ID)) + geom_line()

SIR model with demography

SIRdem_tau <- function (x, params) {
S <- x[2]
I <- x[3]
R <- x[4]
N <- S + I + R
beta <- params["beta"]
gamma <- params["gamma"]
mu <- params["mu"]
## Rates
rates <- c(
birth=mu*N,
infection=beta*S*I/N,
recovery=gamma*I,
sdeath=mu*S,
ideath=mu*I,
rdeath=mu*R
)
## Transition matrix with changes in each event
transition_matrix <- list(
birth=c(1,0,0),
infection=c(-1,1,0),
recovery=c(0,-1,1),
deaths=c(-1,0,0),
deathi=c(0,-1,0),
deathr=c(0,0,-1)
)
## Sum of all events
total_rates <- sum(rates)
## Time to the next event
if (total_rates==0)
tau <- Inf
else
tau <- rexp(n=1,rate=total_rates)
## Decide which event will occur
next_event <- sample.int(n=length(rates),size=1,prob=rates/total_rates)
return(x + c(tau, transition_matrix[[next_event]]))
}
nsims <- 10
N <- 500
xstart <- tibble(time=0,S=N-10,I=10,R=0) #initial conditions
params <- c(beta=0.2, gamma= 1/10, mu = 0.02/365) #parameters in units of days
output_all <- tibble(NULL)
for(i in 1:nsims){
x <- as_vector(xstart)
output <- xstart %>% mutate(ID = i)
while ((x["time"] < 200) && (x["I"] > 0)) {
x <- SIRdem_tau(x,params)
output <- output %>% bind_rows(x) %>% mutate(ID = i)
}
output_all <- output_all %>% bind_rows(output)
}
output_all %>% ggplot(aes(time, I, group=ID)) + geom_line()

Assignment

a) Implement tau-leap method for the SIR model with demography suing the same parameters than those used for the direct method, run 10 simulations (80 points)
SIR_tau_leap = function (x, params) { 
S <- x[2]
I <- x[3]
R <- x[4]
N <- S + I + R
beta <- params["beta"]
gamma <- params["gamma"]
mu <- params["mu"]
tau = 1

transmission = rpois(1, lambda = tau * beta * S * I / N) 
birth = rpois(1, lambda = tau * mu * N)
deaths = rpois(1, lambda = tau * mu * S)
deathi = rpois(1, lambda = tau * mu * I)
deathr = rpois(1, lambda = tau * mu * R)
recovery = rpois(1, lambda = tau * gamma * I)
  dS = birth - transmission - deaths
  dI = transmission - recovery - deathi
  dR = recovery - deathr
  return(x + c(tau, c(dS,dI,dR)))
}
nsims <- 10
N <- 500
xstart <- tibble(time=0,S=N-10,I=10,R=0) 
params <- c(beta=0.2, gamma= 1/10, mu = 0.02/365) 
output_all <- tibble(NULL)

for(i in 1:nsims) {
x <- as_vector(xstart)
output <- xstart %>% mutate(ID = i)
while ((x["time"] < 200) && (x["I"] > 0)) {
    x <- SIR_tau_leap(x,params)
    output <- output %>% bind_rows(x) %>% mutate(ID = i)
  }
  output_all <- output_all %>% bind_rows(output)
}
output_all %>% ggplot(aes(time, I, group=ID)) + geom_line()

b) Run 100 simulations, and show the the 5 and 95 confidence intervals instead of each individual run (using the quantile function) (10 points)
nsims <- 100
N <- 500
xstart <- tibble(time=0,S=N-10,I=10,R=0) 
params <- c(beta=0.2, gamma= 1/10, mu = 0.02/365) 
output_100 <- tibble(NULL)

for(i in 1:nsims) {
x <- as_vector(xstart)
output <- xstart %>% mutate(ID = i)

while ((x["time"] < 200) && (x["I"] > 0)) {
    x <- SIR_tau_leap(x,params)
    output <- output %>% bind_rows(x) %>% mutate(ID = i)
  }
  output_100 <- output_100 %>% bind_rows(output)
}
output_100 %>%
  group_by(time) %>%
  summarise(I_05 = quantile(I, probs = 0.05), I_95 = quantile(I, probs = 0.95)) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  ggplot(aes(time,ymin = I_05, ymax = I_95)) +
  geom_ribbon() + geom_line(aes(y = I_05)) + geom_line(aes(y=I_95))

c) In the same plot, compare the 5 and 95 confidence intervals for the direct method and for the tau-leap method, using 100 simulations for each of them. (10 points)
output_tau_leap_CI = output_100 %>%
  group_by(time) %>%
  summarise(I_05 = quantile(I, probs = 0.05), I_95 = quantile(I, probs = 0.95)) %>%
  ungroup()
output_d_CI = output_all %>%
  mutate(time = round(time)) %>%
  group_by(time) %>%
  summarise(I_05 = quantile(I, probs = 0.05), I_95 = quantile(I, probs = 0.95)) %>%
  ungroup()
ggplot() +
  geom_ribbon(data = output_tau_leap_CI, aes(time,ymin = I_05, ymax = I_95, fill = "red"))+
  geom_line(data = output_tau_leap_CI, aes(time,y = I_05, col = "red")) +
  geom_line(data = output_tau_leap_CI, aes(time,y=I_95, col = "red")) +
  geom_ribbon(data = output_d_CI, aes(time,ymin = I_05, ymax = I_95, fill = "blue")) +
  geom_line(data = output_d_CI,aes(time,y = I_05, col = "blue")) +
  geom_line(data = output_d_CI,aes(time,y=I_95, col = "blue"))
